Microtransit GPS Tracking System

Arduino + SIM7000A + Python Backend + Web Frontend

    Overview

This project is a complete real-time GPS tracking system designed for microtransit applications. It uses a cellular-enabled microcontroller to collect GPS data and transmit it to a backend server, which then makes the data available for visualization on a web interface.

System Pipeline
Arduino (SIM7000A)
   ↓
Cellular Network (LTE-M / NB-IoT)
   ↓
Python Backend (API server)
   ↓
Database (location storage)
   ↓
Web Frontend (map visualization)

The system continuously gathers GPS coordinates and updates the vehicle’s position in near real-time.

    Hardware Requirements
Arduino-compatible board (e.g., Arduino Uno)
SIM7000A LTE/NB-IoT/GPRS module
Active SIM card with data plan
GPS antenna (external recommended)
Power supply (stable 5V / 2A recommended)
    Software Requirements
Arduino
Arduino IDE
Botletics SIM7000 Library
SoftwareSerial library (built-in)
Backend
Python 3.x
Flask (or equivalent web framework)
Frontend
Web browser (for viewing location data)
Optional: map library (Leaflet, Google Maps, etc.)
    System Setup
1. Hardware Wiring
SIM7000A	Arduino
TX	Pin 10
RX	Pin 11
GND	GND
VCC	5V

    Ensure proper power supply — unstable power can cause resets.

2. Arduino Setup
Install required libraries:
Botletics SIM7000
Open the Arduino sketch.
Configure the following:
const char APN[] = "Wholesale";
const char HOST[] = "your-server-url.com";
const char PATH[] = "/devices/arduino_01/location";
const char API_KEY[] = "your_api_key";
Upload the code to the Arduino.
    How It Works
Step 1: Initialization
The Arduino establishes communication with the SIM7000 module.
GPS is enabled using:
AT+CGNSPWR=1
Step 2: GPS Data Collection

The system polls GPS data using:

AT+CGNSINF

Example response:

+CGNSINF: 1,1,20260422074935.000,28.146621,-81.822017,...

Where:

1,1 → valid GPS fix
Latitude and Longitude follow immediately after timestamp
Step 3: Data Transmission

Once a valid GPS fix is obtained:

The full raw GPS string is sent to the backend via HTTPS POST.

Example payload:

+CGNSINF: 1,1,20260422074935.000,28.146621,-81.822017,...
Step 4: Backend Processing

The Python server:

Receives the raw GPS string
Parses:
Timestamp
Latitude
Longitude
Stores the data
Makes it available to the frontend
Step 5: Frontend Display

The frontend:

Fetches latest location data
Displays vehicle position on a map
Updates in real time
    Running the Backend
Install dependencies:
pip install flask
Run the server:
python app.py
Ensure your endpoint matches the Arduino configuration:
@app.route('/devices/arduino_01/location', methods=['POST'])
    Example API Request
Headers
POST /devices/arduino_01/location HTTP/1.1
Host: your-server-url.com
X_API_KEY: your_api_key
Content-Type: text/plain
Body
+CGNSINF: 1,1,20260422074935.000,28.146621,-81.822017,...
    Testing the System
Arduino Serial Monitor

Expected output:

MODEM OK
GPS ON
RAWFIX
+CGNSINF: 1,1,...
RSSI 14
GPRS OK
POST OK
Backend Logs

Expected:

Received GPS data
Parsed lat/lon successfully
Stored location
    Troubleshooting
No GPS Fix
Move device outdoors
Ensure antenna is connected
Wait several minutes for first fix
GPRS / LTE Failure
Check SIM card activation
Verify APN settings
Ensure network coverage
No Data on Frontend
Confirm backend is running
Check API key
Verify endpoint URL
Arduino Resets / Freezes
Ensure stable power supply
Reduce memory usage in code
Avoid unnecessary buffers
    Design Decisions
Raw GPS transmission instead of parsed values to:
reduce Arduino memory usage
simplify embedded logic
Server-side parsing for flexibility
Minimal Arduino processing for stability
    Future Improvements
Add JSON formatting for structured data
Improve error handling and retries
Add data buffering when offline
Implement real-time WebSocket updates
Add multiple device tracking support
